Part I : Business Understanding¶

Optimizing App Offers With Starbucks

The objective of this project is to understand what influence a customer to purchase or respond to an offer. The analysis is based on customer’s transaction data, demographic profile, and offer type. The goals of this project are: to combine all three datasets, explore the data, and provide an analysis of which demographic responds to an offer. It is important to note that, the dataset provided for this project is limited and a simplified version of the real Starbucks app. The simulator data has one product only, whereas Starbucks sells dozens of products.

Part II : Data Understanding¶

The data provided by Starbucks contain three files:

  • portfolio.json - containing offer ids and meta data about each offer (duration, type, etc.)
  • profile.json - demographic data for each customer
  • transcript.json - records for transactions, offers received, offers viewed, and offers completed

#define function for values count and percentage
def pct_var(col, df):
    '''Takes the column name and dataframe, returns the value counts of column and percentage'''
    
    pct_cnt = pd.DataFrame(df.groupby(col)[col].count())
    pct_cnt['Percent'] = (pct_cnt[col]/pct_cnt[col].sum())*100
    pct_cnt.sort_values(by='Percent', ascending=True)
    
    return pct_cnt

#Define function for plotting variables
def plot_var(col, df):
    '''Takes the column name and dataframe, returns visual plot of the column'''

    cat_order = df[col].value_counts().index
    sns.countplot(data = df, y = df[col], order=cat_order)
    plt.title('Count')
    plt.ylabel(col)
In [5]:
#Define function for plotting corelation of variable to average amount
def plot_ave(col, avecol, df):
    '''Takes the column name, column to be computed average, and dataframe, returns visual plot of the column'''
    
    ave_comp = df.groupby(df[col])[avecol].mean()
    ave_comp.sort_values(ascending=True)
    
    ave_comp.plot(kind = 'barh');
    plt.title('Average Spend')
    plt.ylabel(col)

#Define function for plotting corellation of variable to frequency/count
def plot_cnt(col, cntcol, df, charttitle):
    '''Takes the column name, column to be counted, and dataframe, returns visual plot of the column'''
                                             
    cnt_comp = df.groupby(df[col]).count()[cntcol]
    cnt_comp.sort_values(ascending=True)
  
    cnt_comp.plot(kind = 'barh');
    plt.title(charttitle)
    plt.xlabel('Count')
    plt.ylabel(col)
In [7]:
#Define function for plotting crosstab of variables
def pltcrosstab(col, cntcol, df, charttitle):
    '''Takes the column name, column to be counted, and dataframe, returns crosstab plot of the column'''

    cross_comp = pd.crosstab(df[cntcol], df[col])
    cross_comp.plot.bar(figsize=(5,3));
    plt.legend(title=col)
    plt.title(charttitle)
    plt.show()
2.2 Inspect portfolio.json file¶

Data Dictionary

  • id (string) - offer id
  • offer_type (string) - type of offer ie BOGO, discount, informational
  • difficulty (int) - minimum required spend to complete an offer
  • reward (int) - reward given for completing an offer
  • duration (int) - time for offer to be open, in days
  • channels (list of strings)

2.4 Inspect transcript.json file¶

Data Dictionary

  • event (str) - record description (ie transaction, offer received, offer viewed, etc.)
  • person (str) - customer id
  • time (int) - time in hours since start of test. The data begins at time t=0
  • value - (dict of strings) - either an offer id or transaction amount depending on the record

# compute membership length based on max date of became_member_on('08-26-2018')

# note:I used Max date in the dataset to compute membership length, instead of today(),
# so that the number of days will not result to false positive result or increased membership length

df_profile['ndays'] = datetime.date(2018, 7, 26)  - df_profile['became_member_on']
df_profile['ndays'] = df_profile['ndays'].dt.days

5.3 Conclusion¶

Both models resulted to 0.97 score and similar important features that are significant to predictive model. The Random Forest Classifier model top 5 features are: the day of the week the offer was completed (wkday_completed), day of the week the offer was viewed (wkday_viewed), rewardvalue, discount offer type, bogo offer type. The Gradient Boosting Classifier model top 5 features are: the day of the week the offer was completed (wkday_completed), discount offer type, bogo offer type, day of the week the offer was viewed (wkday_viewed), and income_code. Between the two models, the common features that are significat to predictive model are:

(1) day of the week the offer was completed (wkday_completed)
(2) day of the week the offer was viewed (wkday_viewed)
(3) discount offer type
(4) bogo offer type

In addition, based on the result of feature analysis, the relationship or correlation between offer completion, average transaction amount spent, and demographic profile of customers. Male, age group 30-60yo, with income of 70K and higher, and customers within a year are most likely to complete an offer. Additionally, sending the offer to customer on Monday is effective because customers are most likely to complete the offer on Monday and Tuesday, regardless of demographic profile. While Female and Other gender code, spend more than Male.

Part VI : Implementation¶

The implementation can be done into the following stages:

  1. Save the data into a database (i.e. SQL or DB2)
  2. Develop a Jupyter Notebook that will:
    • Read the data from database
    • Define callable functions to perform the data cleanup and transformation as implemented in this Jupyter Notebook.
    • Develop callable functions to perform feature analysis and visualization, which can be deployed into online dashboard.
    • Define callable functions that will train and execute two predictive models.
  3. Deploy the model into a hosting environment and can be called from applications
